    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from xAI\'s SEC filings (likely an S-1 prospectus or 10-K/10-Q), here is a summary of the revenue recognition policies, segment reporting, and revenue breakdowns for the **AI segment** and **Grok**.\n\n### **1. AI Segment Revenue Streams & Recognition Policies**\n\nThe AI segment generates revenue from three primary service categories, each with specific recognition policies:\n\n*   **A. Advertising Revenue (primarily from X platform)**\n    *   **Recognition:** Revenue is recognized **in the period the advertising is delivered**, evidenced by a user engaging with the ad (e.g., impression, click, conversion) in a manner that satisfies the advertiser\'s selected criteria.\n    *   **Principal vs. Agent (Key Judgment):**\n        *   **Gross Basis (Principal):** For ads sold directly through X, xAI controls the ad service before transfer, serves the ads, and fulfills the engagement criteria.\n        *   **Net Basis (Agent):** For ads sold via Supply Side Platform (SSP) partners, the SSP controls the inventory and pricing. xAI receives a revenue share and acts as an agent, recognizing only its net commission.\n    *   **Seasonality:** Advertising revenue is highest in Q4 (year-end spending) and lowest in Q1.\n\n*   **B. AI Solutions & Infrastructure Revenue (including Grok)**\n    This category includes subscriptions, data licensing, and API access, recognized as follows:\n\n    *   **Subscriptions (X Premium & Grok tiers):**\n        *   **Recognition:** **Ratably on a straight-line basis** over the subscription term (ranging from month-to-month to one year).\n        *   **Products:** Includes various Grok tiers (Basic, SuperGrok, SuperGrok Heavy, SuperGrok Lite) and X subscriptions.\n\n    *   **Data Licensing Arrangements:**\n        *   **Recognition:** Generally recognized **ratably** over the license period (from month-to-month to two years) as the customer consumes and benefits from the data.\n        *   **Complex Arrangements:** For contracts with multiple performance obligations (e.g., historical IP vs. future IP), revenue is allocated based on standalone selling price. Minimum guarantees are recognized straight-line, with excess royalties recognized contractually.\n\n    *   **API Access (to Grok models):**\n        *   **Primary Obligation:** To stand ready to provide access to the platform.\n        *   **Recognition:**\n            *   **Subscription/Stand-Ready Access:** Recognized **ratably** over the contract term.\n            *   **Usage-Based Arrangements:** Recognized **as services are consumed** (as tokens are processed or compute hours are utilized).\n\n*   **C. General & Significant Judgments**\n    *   **Cost of Revenue:** Includes infrastructure (data centers, cloud computing, depreciation), revenue share, payment processing fees, creator payments, and allocated labor/overhead.\n    *   **Significant Judgment (Starshield):** Estimating total contract costs and measuring progress for Starshield government contracts requires significant management judgment regarding labor, materials, cost allocation, and technological changes.\n    *   **Deferred Revenue:** Recorded when cash is received in advance of performance, primarily for Space and Connectivity enterprise/government contracts.\n\n### **2. Segment Reporting**\n\nxAI reports revenue across **three main segments**:\n\n1.  **Space Segment:** Revenue from **Launch Services** and **Launch & Development** (government programs).\n2.  **Connectivity Segment:** Revenue from **Consumer** (Starlink subscribers) and **Enterprise & Government** (including Starlink Mobile) services.\n3.  **AI Segment:** Revenue from **Advertising** and **AI Solutions & Infrastructure** (as detailed above).\n\nThe AI segment is highlighted as a key growth driver, with a focus on scaling Grok and the vertically integrated platform.\n\n### **3. AI Segment Revenue Breakdowns (from MD&A Analysis)**\n\nThe Management\'s Discussion and Analysis (MD&A) sections provide insight into the drivers of AI segment revenue changes:\n\n*   **Full Year 2025 vs. 2024:**\n    *   AI Segment Revenue **increased $581M (22.2%)**.\n    *   **Drivers:** +$116M in **Advertising** (recovery from lost partners) and +$465M in **AI Solutions & Infrastructure** (led by +$365M in X/Grok **subscriptions** and +$88M in **data licensing**).\n\n*   **Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025 (One Excerpt):**\n    *   AI Segment Revenue **increased $91M (12.5%)**.\n    *   **Drivers:** **AI Solutions & Infrastructure** revenue increased $191M (from +$177M **subscriptions** and +$12M **data licensing**), partially offset by a **$100M decrease in Advertising** due to an ad platform overhaul.\n\n*   **Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025 (Another Excerpt):**\n    *   AI Segment Revenue **increased $91M**.\n    *   **Drivers:** Higher **X and Grok subscriptions**. (This is part of a larger consolidated discussion that also mentions a $782M increase in Connectivity and a $246M decrease in Space revenue).\n\n*   **2024 vs. 2023:**\n    *   AI Segment Revenue **decreased $341M (11.5%)**.\n    *   **Drivers:** **Advertising revenue decreased $595M** (loss of partners), partially offset by a **$254M increase in AI Solutions & Infrastructure** (from +$157M **subscriptions** and +$90M **data licensing**).\n\n### **4. Market Opportunity & Monetization Strategy (Context)**\n\n*   **Consumer AI Subscriptions:** Market sized by global population (5.5B people) and weighted average monthly subscription revenue, resulting in an estimated **~$760B annual market opportunity**.\n*   **Digital Advertising:** Targeted as a **~$600B global market** (2025), leveraging X\'s scale and AI-driven ad tools.\n*   **Enterprise Applications:** Focus on growing adoption of **Grok Business, Grok Enterprise, and API** solutions.\n*   **Grok Development:** Emphasis on high "model velocity," with plans for advanced, multi-trillion parameter models to strengthen the subscription value proposition.\n\nIn summary, xAI\'s AI segment revenue is recognized based on specific performance obligations across advertising, subscriptions, licensing, and API services, with careful application of gross/net principles. Segment reporting clearly delineates the AI business from its Space and Connectivity operations. Revenue trends show a shift from volatility in advertising to growth in subscriptions and licensing as core drivers for the segment.',
