:** The filing explicitly states that the company expects a **"multi-year investment horizon"** before the AI segment\'s infrastructure deployments translate into sustained positive Adjusted EBITDA. Profitability is a long-term goal contingent on scaling revenue and achieving economies of scale in compute infrastructure.\n\n### 3. **Customer Acquisition Costs (CAC)**\nThe documents **do not disclose a specific Customer Acquisition Cost** metric for the AI segment.\n\n*   The relevant costs would fall under **SG&A** (marketing, sales compensation) and potentially parts of **Cost of Revenue** (payment processor fees, revenue share).\n*   The company states it expects SG&A to "increase in absolute dollars to support growth" but to "decrease as a percentage of revenue over time" as it reduces operating costs.\n\n### 4. **Unit Economics & Key Drivers**\nThe unit economics are directly tied to the **cost of compute**, which is described as the main driver of the cost per token for both training and inference.\n\n*   **Primary Cost Driver:** The capital and operational cost of building and running AI compute infrastructure (data centers, processors, power). The filing notes that for most companies, ~70% of capital costs are for processors and IT equipment.\n*   **Strategic Goal:** The company aims to lower its **cost per token** through vertical integration, improving data center construction costs, reducing power costs, and increasing cluster throughput. This is critical for making AI services (like Grok) economically viable at scale.\n*   **Revenue Model:** Revenue is generated from:\n    *   Consumer & Enterprise Subscriptions (X, Grok tiers)\n    *   Data Licensing Arrangements\n    *   API Access to Grok models\n*   The documents do not provide metrics like average revenue per user (ARPU) or gross margin per subscription.\n\n### Summary Table of Key Disclosed Figures (AI Segment)\n\n| Metric | Q1 2026 | Full Year 2025 | Full Year 2024 | Key Disclosed Trend / Driver |\